04446nam a22007215i 9780812293050DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122930507 a10.9783/97808122930502doi  a(DE-B1597)481923  a(OCoLC)987955882  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBM645.P7bV35 2017eb 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a296.3/112231 aWeiss, Dov, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPious Irreverence :bConfronting God in Rabbinic Judaism /cDov Weiss. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Manuscripts, Critical Editions, and Translations Used in the Text -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Confrontation as Sin -- tChapter 2. From Sin to Virtue -- tChapter 3. Varieties of Confrontation -- tChapter 4. Confrontation as Ethics -- tChapter 5. The Humanization of God -- tChapter 6. Divine Concessions -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJudaism is often described as a religion that tolerates, even celebrates arguments with God. Unlike Christianity and Islam, it is said, Judaism endorses a tradition of protest as first expressed in the biblical stories of Abraham, Job, and Jeremiah. In Pious Irreverence, Dov Weiss has written the first scholarly study of the premodern roots of this distinctively Jewish theology of protest, examining its origins and development in the rabbinic age.Weiss argues that this particular Jewish relationship to the divine is rooted in the most canonical of rabbinic texts even as he demonstrates that in ancient Judaism the idea of debating God was itself a matter of debate. By elucidating competing views and exploring their theological assumptions, the book challenges the scholarly claim that the early rabbis conceived of God as a morally perfect being whose goodness had to be defended in the face of biblical accounts of unethical divine action. Pious Irreverence examines the ways in which the rabbis searched the words of the Torah for hidden meanings that could grant them the moral authority to express doubt about, and frustration with, the biblical God. Using characters from the Bible as their mouthpieces, they often challenged God's behavior, even in a few remarkable instances, envisioning God conceding error, declaring to the protestor, "You have taught Me something; I will nullify My decree and accept your word."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aProvidence and government of GodxJudaism. 4aJewish Studies. 4aReligion. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUPP eBook Package 2016z978311066591840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229305040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293050.jpg  a978-3-11-055030-6  Penn Press eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066591-8  UPP eBook Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK